ause the information is widely scattered in books written by specialists for specialists. Recognizing this fact, B. Sprague Allen has taken a corner of the vast field and discussed the development of taste in England during the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries. His book is an account of taste, that is, the likes and dislikes of the men who built and furnished houses and laid out gardens in this period of English culture. Their taste is revealed to a hitherto unrecognized extent in diaries, letters, essays, and plays, and is an index of English civilization. Allen has thus been concerned with the whole complex pattern of living and has made us think and feel and see with the faculties of the cultivated Englishman of two or three hundred years ago.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAesthetics. 0aArt and literature. 0aCivilization. 0aEnglish literature. 0aKünste, Bildende Kunst allgemein. 0aKünste, Bildende Kunst allgemein. 4aAesthetics -- History. 4aArt and literature. 4aEnglish literature -- 18th century -- History and criticism. 4aEnglish literature -- Early modern, 1500-1700 -- History and criticism. 4aGreat Britain -- Civilization. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Complete eBook Packagez9783110353488oZDB-23-HCO08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Literature eBook Packagez9783110353501oZDB-23-HLI08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z97831104422120 cprintz978067472985840uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067472986540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674729865423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674729865.jpg  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBAC